# TinkerPad — Two-Year Plan

*Written 2026-07-03. This is a narrative snapshot of the roadmap, not the roadmap
itself. The **lit backlog is the single source of truth** for what work exists, its
order, and its detail — run `lit backlog` for the live queue. This document captures
what the ticket queue cannot: the whole-picture rationale, the horizon story, and
where each epic traces back to [`PROJECT.md`](./PROJECT.md). If this doc and lit
disagree, lit wins; if this doc and PROJECT.md disagree on intent, PROJECT.md wins.*

---

## Where we are (verified, not assumed)

The core loop — **describe → generate → store → discover → use → remix** — is
**built and verified end-to-end** as of this writing. Driven live through a real
browser against `just dev`:

- Landing page (redesigned: design-token system, light/dark mode, nav, hero,
  create widget) renders and functions.
- Loopback dev login completes the real session dance (CSRF state round-trip,
  cookie minting) with no GitHub app required.
- A prompt typed into the box produced a working playground via the local tmux
  driver running Claude Code: a bouncing-ball physics simulator with presets,
  sliders, and live canvas — stored, served from the sandboxed content origin,
  and playable.
- Player chrome works: attribution, recipe display, Refine input, Remix button,
  Copy Prompt.

One real bug was found and fixed during verification: the OAuth callback URL
defaulted to `127.0.0.1` while browsers visit `localhost`; cookies are
hostname-scoped, so the CSRF state cookie never arrived at the callback and every
dev login failed. The fix (one line in the shared server config) landed as its own
commit.

**Implication for the plan:** the foundation is real. Everything below is
deepening, hardening, and reach — not rescue.

---

## The shape of two years

The backlog holds **22 epics**. Every epic traces to one of PROJECT.md's two
pillars (*frictionless creation*, *the commons*), its safety mandate, or one of
its explicitly open decisions. Nothing was invented from thin air.

Detail follows grooming discipline: near-term tickets are implementer-ready;
far-term tickets are deliberately sparse (a sharp title and the capability, no
file names, no designs) because detail written years early is fiction that rots.
Detail gets added as work rises toward the top — never before.

### Horizon 1 — now → ~3 months: finish the front door

The groomed near-term queue, unchanged by this planning pass:

| Epic | What it finishes |
|---|---|
| `design-pw7` | Apply the new design system everywhere it isn't yet: commons page, player chrome, homepage preview grid, error pages, favicon/metadata |
| `discovery-rye` (near half) | Tags, search bar + tag filter, commons pagination |
| `profile-ek4` | My-playgrounds page, OpenGraph cards, public creator pages |
| `homelab-28m` | Deploy stage 2: two-origin server config, generation toggle |
| `cloudflare-8le` | Deploy stage 3: Workers entry point, D1/R2/KV adapters, cookie hardening |
| `history-3o7` (remainder) | Durable per-turn provider context (blocked on the deploy stages) |

### Horizon 2 — ~3–9 months: make it real and safe

The prerequisites of a genuinely public TinkerPad. Safety outranks social here
because PROJECT.md says safety is designed in from day one, never bolted on.

| Epic | Why it exists |
|---|---|
| `providers` | The tmux driver proves the provider seam but cannot run in the cloud. An API-based Claude driver behind the same seam makes cloud generation real; streaming progress makes the wait feel alive. |
| `sandbox` | Adversarial audit of the one enforcement boundary (iframe sandbox, content-origin CSP, two-origin split) plus per-identity rate limits and quotas. Precedes broad public exposure. |
| `quality` | Self-containment enforced, not hoped for: validation at the storage boundary rejects artifacts with external references. One enforcer, no per-feature checks. |
| `ops` | A *tested* backup/restore path for the commons, logs, minimal metrics. The commons is the product; losing it is existential. |

### Horizon 3 — ~9–18 months: deepen the loop

| Epic | Why it exists |
|---|---|
| `moderation` | The sandbox contains what is *dangerous*; moderation catches what is *unwanted*. Report button, unlist state, admin review queue, prompt screening. |
| `editing` | Resolves a PROJECT.md open decision (regenerate vs direct edit vs both). Baseline lands first: view-source and download — portability is the point of self-containment. |
| `social` | Stars, view counts, remix lineage tree. Lineage is already tracked; it deserves a face. These signals feed trending. |
| `versions` | The user surface over the history epic's provenance data: browse versions, view any, branch from one. |
| `discovery-rye` (far half) | Preview thumbnails, the playground-types taxonomy from PROJECT.md (design / data-explorer / concept-map / document-critique / diff-review / code-map), trending, semantic search. |

### Horizon 4 — ~18–24 months: reach and bets

Deliberately sparse; these get detail when they get close.

| Epic | The bet |
|---|---|
| `collections` | Curation compounds the commons: featured, playground-of-the-day, weekly tinker challenge. |
| `embed` | A playground in a blog post is the same sandboxed iframe against the content origin — no new rules. Embed snippets + oEmbed. |
| `onboarding` | Example gallery and prompt tips *beside* the box, never in front of it — creation stays frictionless. |
| `a11y` | WCAG AA and keyboard operability on all chrome we own (playground content is user-generated and out of scope). |
| `api` | The commons as a platform: public read API and an MCP server so agents can search and spin up playgrounds — agent-native creation matches how playgrounds were born. |
| `accounts` | More identity providers, settings, deletion policy (the commons outlives its authors), the anonymous-creation decision. |
| `economics` | **Decision-gated.** Who pays for generation — platform, BYOK, or credits — is the main cost lever and shapes the whole model. Decide before building. |
| `education` | The speculative big bet: playgrounds as classroom instruments. Validate demand before writing code. |

---

## Structural facts worth knowing

- **Cross-epic dependencies are explicit edges in lit**, not folklore: the
  history epic blocks the versions surface; stars/views block trending. Within an
  epic, rank (not dependency edges) carries the order.
- **Two epics are decision-gated** (`economics`, and the deeper half of
  `editing`): they need a product decision before implementation children exist.
  These are the open decisions PROJECT.md left open on purpose.
- **The deploy story is staged**: dev loopback (done) → homelab → Cloudflare.
  Real cloud *generation* additionally needs the API provider driver — adapters
  alone don't make generation work on Workers.

## What this plan refuses to do

Consistent with PROJECT.md's "what TinkerPad is NOT": no blank-canvas editor, no
general app hosting, no private-by-default, no playground that needs a live
backend. Any future epic that violates self-containment or splits the sandbox
enforcement across features is wrong by construction, regardless of how
attractive the feature is.
